00:32:54.850 --> 00:33:00.480
rewarded, at least monetarily,
for this passion that he had?

00:33:00.480 --> 00:33:03.370
And also, yourself as a
writer, and writers in general

00:33:03.370 --> 00:33:07.260
also, being such hard workers
and not being [? venerated. ?]

00:33:07.260 --> 00:33:07.760
I think--

00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:09.385
RICHARD MUNSON: Boy,
is that the truth.

00:33:12.280 --> 00:33:15.300
You know, I'm not exactly
answering your question,

00:33:15.300 --> 00:33:18.370
but let me try an angle and
you can tell me if I get there.

00:33:18.370 --> 00:33:21.180
He actually could have
been amazingly wealthy.

00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:23.490
I mean, when he sold
his electric motor

00:33:23.490 --> 00:33:26.304
patents to George Westinghouse,
he was living high on the hog.

00:33:26.304 --> 00:33:27.720
As I said, he was
eating his meals

00:33:27.720 --> 00:33:30.550
at Delmonico's every
night, filet mignon.

00:33:30.550 --> 00:33:34.710
He lived in a large apartment
at the Waldorf Astoria, probably

00:33:34.710 --> 00:33:37.260
the best hotel then
in New York City.

00:33:37.260 --> 00:33:39.390
He got tons of money.

00:33:39.390 --> 00:33:44.790
But Westinghouse, in large
part because JP Morgan--

00:33:44.790 --> 00:33:49.650
the banker who was not exactly
a nice man, he wasn't--

00:33:49.650 --> 00:33:53.160
tried to squeeze out George
Westinghouse not long

00:33:53.160 --> 00:33:54.540
after the Niagara project.

00:33:54.540 --> 00:33:56.400
Which is, you know, they
obviously spent a lot of money

00:33:56.400 --> 00:33:57.240
to make this happen.

00:33:57.240 --> 00:33:59.250
And so they were a
little cash short.

00:33:59.250 --> 00:34:01.594
And the economy sort of
just does its cycles.

00:34:01.594 --> 00:34:03.010
And this was in
one of the cycles.

00:34:03.010 --> 00:34:06.900
So Westinghouse was
in not great shape.

00:34:06.900 --> 00:34:09.840
And JP Morgan basically
tried to squeeze him out.

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:14.250
And said, you know, you
either cut expenses immensely,

00:34:14.250 --> 00:34:16.590
or you give your
company to me, and I'll

00:34:16.590 --> 00:34:19.020
create the total
electricity trust, just

00:34:19.020 --> 00:34:22.120
like what he did with
the steel industry.

00:34:22.120 --> 00:34:26.460
So Westinghouse goes to Tesla
and says, I'm in a real jam

00:34:26.460 --> 00:34:27.370
here.

00:34:27.370 --> 00:34:29.489
You know, I'm about
to lose my company.

00:34:29.489 --> 00:34:35.870
And you have this royalty,
$2.50 per horsepower of motor.

00:34:35.870 --> 00:34:38.639
I can't afford it.

00:34:38.639 --> 00:34:41.310
Tesla is sitting there,
he has all the cards.

00:34:41.310 --> 00:34:42.079
He has the patent.

00:34:42.079 --> 00:34:44.510
He has the contract.

00:34:44.510 --> 00:34:46.650
And he's not a really
good businessman.

00:34:46.650 --> 00:34:49.290
So he turns to
George Westinghouse

00:34:49.290 --> 00:34:54.540
and says, oh, you've
been nice to me.

00:34:54.540 --> 00:34:58.770
You're the one who will bring
my electric motor to the world.

00:34:58.770 --> 00:35:01.800
I'm willing to tear
up my contract.

00:35:01.800 --> 00:35:05.070
He tore up a billion
dollars of money

00:35:05.070 --> 00:35:06.280
that would have come his way.

00:35:06.280 --> 00:35:08.389
Simply, number one,
I don't think he

00:35:08.389 --> 00:35:09.430
was a great business man.

00:35:09.430 --> 00:35:11.460
He certainly was a
horrible negotiator.

00:35:11.460 --> 00:35:13.260
But because he was an idealist.

00:35:13.260 --> 00:35:15.782
Here was a man who was going
to bring his invention, which

00:35:15.782 --> 00:35:17.740
he thought was the greatest
thing in the world.

00:35:17.740 --> 00:35:21.150
And I'm not [INAUDIBLE]
argue with that.

00:35:21.150 --> 00:35:24.210
And for that, he was
willing to sacrifice

00:35:24.210 --> 00:35:26.187
an amazing amount of wealth.

00:35:26.187 --> 00:35:28.020
I'm not sure if that
answered your question,

00:35:28.020 --> 00:35:29.490
but I like that story better.

