There is a very
interesting MIT connection,

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:10.090
which I probably shouldn't say.

00:36:10.090 --> 00:36:15.250
So in his later years,
when he was, to be honest,

00:36:15.250 --> 00:36:18.140
a little bit senile, but
also had flashes of genius,

00:36:18.140 --> 00:36:20.140
he would have birthday
parties for himself.

00:36:20.140 --> 00:36:21.910
And he would invite reporters.

00:36:21.910 --> 00:36:25.060
And really, 50 of the major
reporters from the "New York

00:36:25.060 --> 00:36:27.310
Times," the "New York
Herald," "Time Magazine,"

00:36:27.310 --> 00:36:29.710
all these people would
come and sit at his feet

00:36:29.710 --> 00:36:33.570
for like five hours as the
great man would ramble on.

00:36:33.570 --> 00:36:37.270
90% of the time about
gibberish, and 10%

00:36:37.270 --> 00:36:39.820
of the time about something,
oh my god, you know?

00:36:39.820 --> 00:36:46.600
So one of his visions during
these birthday parties

00:36:46.600 --> 00:36:49.990
was a death beam.

00:36:49.990 --> 00:36:53.610
Something like Star Wars
that could zap battleships

00:36:53.610 --> 00:36:56.100
and airplanes out of the air.

00:36:56.100 --> 00:36:58.884
All right, we're talking
in the early 1940s,

00:36:58.884 --> 00:37:00.550
at a time when we're
about to go to war.

00:37:00.550 --> 00:37:05.560
And the thought of Nikola Tesla
dying and he had the designs--

00:37:05.560 --> 00:37:09.580
possibly-- for a
death beam did not

00:37:09.580 --> 00:37:11.530
make the Federal
Bureau of Investigation

00:37:11.530 --> 00:37:15.580
all that excited about allowing
his papers to go anywhere

00:37:15.580 --> 00:37:16.250
in the world.

00:37:16.250 --> 00:37:22.710
So they hired an MIT physicist
and assembled all of his papers

00:37:22.710 --> 00:37:25.330
together, which
were in huge boxes.

00:37:25.330 --> 00:37:28.750
And he spent at least a week,
if not a couple of weeks,

00:37:28.750 --> 00:37:32.620
being overseen by Naval
intelligence and federal FBI

00:37:32.620 --> 00:37:34.330
agents as he went
through the documents.

00:37:34.330 --> 00:37:37.660
And there was one
that he actually

00:37:37.660 --> 00:37:42.280
put the top secret clearance
on, because it was, in his mind,

00:37:42.280 --> 00:37:48.610
close enough to being practical
that it needed to be considered

00:37:48.610 --> 00:37:49.960
to be top secret.

00:37:49.960 --> 00:37:52.120
The rest of it, he says,
basically the ramblings

00:37:52.120 --> 00:37:54.010
of an old man.

00:37:54.010 --> 00:37:57.130
And I say that feeling old.

00:37:57.130 --> 00:38:00.040
But here's the
critical question.

00:38:00.040 --> 00:38:02.320
Does anybody know
who the MIT professor

00:38:02.320 --> 00:38:06.370
was that they hired to do this?

00:38:06.370 --> 00:38:07.746
John Trump.

00:38:07.746 --> 00:38:09.370
John Trump was a
member of the National

00:38:09.370 --> 00:38:10.420
Academy of Engineering.

00:38:10.420 --> 00:38:13.672
He won the National
Academy of Sciences award.

00:38:13.672 --> 00:38:15.880
He also happens to be the
uncle of the 45th President

00:38:15.880 --> 00:38:17.924
of the United States.

00:38:17.924 --> 00:38:20.071
How's that?

00:38:20.071 --> 00:38:22.570
And in fact, when the current
president of the United States

00:38:22.570 --> 00:38:26.260
was running for office, he
would refer to his uncle

00:38:26.260 --> 00:38:28.480
as somebody really bright.

00:38:28.480 --> 00:38:33.466
Notice that I have a lot of
smart genes, I'm really bright.

00:38:33.466 --> 00:38:35.620
And it's because that's
my only sort of Boston

00:38:35.620 --> 00:38:39.990
connection through MIT
was through Mr. Trump.

00:38:39.990 --> 00:38:40.968
What other questions?

